This HIT does NOT work from Internet Explorer.

(If you are using Internet Explorer browser (IE) please switch to Chrome or Firefox)

Important! Please read Instructions and Examples before you begin

Instructions (click to collapse / expand)

You are given a short document.

Your goal is to find all the main aspects contained in the document and map each and every sentence in the document to the relevant aspect(s).

Think of an aspect as a high-level topic discussed among similar types of documents.

How to Choose Aspects:

  • Choose the main aspects - Good aspects are the dominant aspects in the document and clearly associated with their linked sentences.
  • Not too generic aspect - For example, In a document about Chimpanzees - "Animal", "Monkey" or "Chimpanzees" are bad aspects. Better aspects may be "Behavior" or "Habitat" (if there are relevant sentences associated with them).
  • Not too specific aspects - Using a phrase in a sentence as an aspect. For example, in a global warming document, choosing "melting" as an aspect is too specific. Better aspects may be "environmental impact" or "sea-level rising".
  • Not technical aspects - Using "women", "teenage", "age" or "In 2022" are usually too technical and should be avoided.

Important Notes:

  • First, read the document briefly to uncover the main aspects.
  • Each sentence must be mapped to at least one aspect (overlaps between different aspects are allowed).
  • You cannot map a text-span shorter than a full sentence.
  • The total number of aspects for the whole document should be at least 3.

A bonus will be given for quality HITs.

Please read the example below.
Examples (click to collapse / expand)


Document 1

Tag each sentence from the aspect list, add new apsects when needed

  6. -

  8. The 1997 attack on Louima, a black Haitian immigrant, sparked protests and prompted a Justice Department investigation into whether the New York Police Department fosters abuse of minorities by not cracking down on excessive force.

  9. -

  10. Prosecutors had accused Rosario of lying because he ''did not want to be labeled a rat.''

  11. -

  12. Defense attorney Richard Levitt said Rosario would appeal.

  13. -

  14. Rosario faces up to five years in prison; no sentencing date was set.
